article.headline: O'Neal posts 29 points, 11 rebounds in big road win

images.name: O'Neal_Jermaine 020303 inline
images.caption: Can Jermaine O'Neal and the Pacers sneak into the playoffs?

article.linkText: Pacers react just fine without Miller, beating the Kings
article.story:
SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- When the Sacramento Kings stumbled to one of their worst performances in an outstanding season, the Indiana Pacers were happy to take advantage. Jermaine O'Neal had 29 points and 11 rebounds as the Pacers shook off Reggie Miller's suspension Sunday to win in the NBA's toughest road arena, 97-86. Though the Pacers earned the victory with a strong fourth-quarter rally and outstanding defense on Chris Webber and his teammates, O'Neal and coach Isiah Thomas both declined the credit for their fifth consecutive victory over Sacramento, which had its worst shooting game of the season. "We just seem to catch them at the right time," Thomas said. "When you're 29-2 at home, the odds start working in the visitors' favor. I feel bad for the next team that comes in here." Austin Croshere scored 19 points in a reserve role as Indiana surprised the NBA-leading Kings without Miller, who served the first game of his two-game suspension for fighting with Kobe Bryant. Though the Pacers were disgusted that Miller got the same suspension as Bryant, who appeared to start the fight Friday night, they responded with one of their most tenacious defensive games of the season, holding high-flying Sacramento less than 35 percent shooting for the first time this season. The Kings went just 19-for-33 on free throws, also their worst percentage of the season. "All the other stuff aside, we make free throws, we win the game," Scot Pollard said. "We shot the ball poorly from everywhere we could possibly shoot the ball poorly from. I don't credit their defense for any of that. I don't think they did anything to take us out of our game." Jonathan Bender had 16 points and nine rebounds for the Pacers, who handed the Kings just their third home loss of the season. Indiana won its second consecutive in Arco Arena, where the Kings are 62-11 over the past two campaigns. After staying close in the first three quarters while the Kings struggled with foul trouble, the Pacers went on a 21-7 run over an eight-minute span in the fourth quarter, taking the lead for good on O'Neal's jumper with 4:58 left. Miller's absence gave extra responsibility to O'Neal, and he responded. "This was the first time we were able to really get him going," said center Brad Miller, who arrived in a trade 12 days earlier. "Everyone knew we had to step it up with Reggie out. Bender hit some shots, and (Ron) Artest can create. I come from Chicago -- we've been short-handed all year." Webber scored 13 points on 2-for-16 shooting. Webber, who had 51 points and 26 rebounds in the Pacers' visit to Sacramento last season, and Peja Stojakovic spent much of the game in foul trouble as the officials called a stifling 51 fouls in the game, choking the Kings' normally free-flowing offense. "We did recall that," O'Neal said of Webber's huge game last season. "Overall, we tried to make him take tough shots. It's hard to double him. They have so many shooters. I don't think it was so much of what I did. He just missed shots." Indiana closed a four-game road trip by snapping a two-game losing streak. Artest had 11 points while starting in Miller's absence. But the Pacers' most surprising contributor was Croshere, who scored 11 points in the fourth quarter and finished 10-for-10 from the line in one of the high points of his disappointing season. Mike Bibby had 19 points for the Kings, and Stojakovic added 18 on 7-for-18 shooting. "We just played bad today. It happens," Stojakovic said. "They came into the game real aggressive, especially at the end. We just have to bounce back as soon as possible." Neither team was happy with a choppy, disjointed first half called extremely closely by the officials. Doug Christie -- who didn't score in 27 minutes -- spent time on the sideline with Webber and Stojakovic because of foul trouble. Stojakovic also got a rare technical for protesting a call. Game notes
Indiana and Dallas are the only teams to beat Sacramento twice this season. ... Miller also will miss the home game Tuesday against Orlando. ... Last season, Indiana won 93-91 in overtime in Arco. ... The start time was changed twice in recent weeks as NBC dropped the game from its national schedule in favor of a Wizards game -- then added it back to the schedule after Michael Jordan got injured. Still, Arco Arena was full at game time.
